    • Field Detail

      • REAL

        public static final ColumnType<java.lang.Void> REAL
        Complex id for columns holding 64 bit double values. Data can be accessed, for example, via Readers.numericReader(Column).

      • INTEGER_53_BIT

        public static final ColumnType<java.lang.Void> INTEGER_53_BIT
        Complex id for columns holding 64 bit double values with no fractional digits. Data can be accessed, for example, via Readers.numericReader(Column).

        Please note: The maximum / minimum value that can be stored without loss of information is +/- 2^53-1 , or +/- 9,007,199,254,740,991. Therefore, casting this column's values to int leads to loss of information for values smaller / larger than Integer.MIN_VALUE / Integer.MAX_VALUE.

      • NOMINAL

        public static final ColumnType<java.lang.String> NOMINAL
        Complex id for columns holding categorical strings. Data can be read categorical or as String. This can be done, for example, via Readers.categoricalReader(Column) or Readers.objectReader(Column, Class).

      • TIME

        public static final ColumnType<java.time.LocalTime> TIME
        Complex id for columns holding nanoseconds of a day. Data can be read numeric or as LocalTime. This can be done, for example, via Readers.numericReader(Column) or Readers.objectReader(Column, Class).

      • DATETIME

        public static final ColumnType<java.time.Instant> DATETIME
        Complex id for columns holding 64 bit UTC timestamps (seconds), and 32Bit fraction of a second (nanoseconds, optional). Data can be read as Instant. This can be done, for example, via Readers.objectReader(Column, Class).

      • TEXT

        public static final ColumnType<java.lang.String> TEXT
        Complex id for columns holding non-categorical strings. Data can be read as String. This can be done, for example, via Readers.objectReader(Column, Class).

      • TEXTSET

        public static final ColumnType<StringSet> TEXTSET
        Complex id for columns holding sets of strings. Data can be read as StringSet. This can be done, for example, via Readers.objectReader(Column, Class).
